cell("markdown","---\n## Phase −1 — Theoretical Foundation\n\n### Matrices as Transformations\n> 📖 *From Linear Algebra §3.1:* Matrices can be thought of as objects that transform vectors.\n\nA matrix is a grid of numbers. An $m \\times n$ matrix has $m$ rows and $n$ columns.\nIf we multiply an $m \\times n$ matrix by an $n$-dimensional vector, we get an $m$-dimensional vector.\n\n$$\\begin{bmatrix} a & b \\\\ c & d \\end{bmatrix} \\begin{bmatrix} x \\\\ y \\end{bmatrix} = x \\begin{bmatrix} a \\\\ c \\end{bmatrix} + y \\begin{bmatrix} b \\\\ d \\end{bmatrix} = \\begin{bmatrix} ax + by \\\\ cx + dy \\end{bmatrix}$$\n\nNotice that the columns of the matrix dictate where the basis vectors $\\langle 1, 0 \\rangle$ and $\\langle 0, 1 \\rangle$ land!\n\n### Matrix Multiplication\n> 📖 *From Linear Algebra §3.2:* When multiplying two matrices $A$ and $B$, the result $AB$ represents applying transformation $B$ first, then transformation $A$.\n\nThe element in row $i$ and column $j$ of the product matrix $C = AB$ is the **dot product** of the $i$-th row of $A$ and the $j$-th column of $B$.\n\n$$C_{ij} = \\sum_{k=1}^n A_{ik} B_{kj}$$\n\n**Important:** Matrix multiplication is NOT commutative. $AB \\neq BA$ in general. Order matters!"),
